	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>ECDPM backgrounder and update</h1>

			
			<h4>
												28 February 2007
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> ECDPM has posted a background briefing and update on the SADC-EU EPA negotiations. The briefing looks at the issues and challenges faced while the update surveys the progress of the negotiations. The update notes the Pacific region’s limited interest in a common regional approach to trade in goods, and a focus on trade in services and a regional approach to fisheries. It highlights the specific architecture of an EPA agreement favoured by the Pacific ACP members (PACP): a framework agreement and subsidiary agreements to which PACP members can opt in as appropriate, and notes the EC’s lukewarm response to this approach on the grounds of WTO compatibility and lack of ambition. The EC is ‘strongly pushing for an all-inclusive EPA’. The development dimension and the question of additional financing for EPA-related adjustments are seen as key.</p><p> A summary of the January 2007 joint technical working group conclusions described a ‘constructive atmosphere’ for discussions and committed the partners to ‘conclude the negotiations in 2007 in time for the EPA to enter into force on January 1st 2008’. A ministerial meeting is tentatively scheduled for March 2007. </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Summary of the January 2007 EC-Pacific technical working group meeting</p><p>

<a href="http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2007/february/tradoc_133246.pdf" target="_self">http://trade.ec.europa.eu/doclib/docs/2007/february/tradoc_133246.pdf</a> <br/> </p><p> ECDPM overview </p><p>
<a href="http://www.ecdpm.org/Web_ECDPM/Web/Content/Navigation.nsf/index2?readform&amp;http://www.ecdpm.org/Web_ECDPM/Web/Content/Content.nsf/7732def81dddfa7ac1256c240034fe65/b38a277a1ad9d1dec1257220005389f0?OpenDocument" target="_self">http://www.ecdpm.org/Web_ECDPM/Web/Content/Navigation.nsf/index2?readfor...</a> </p><p> ECDPM update</p><p>

<a href="http://www.ecdpm.org/Web_ECDPM/Web/Content/Navigation.nsf/index2?readform&amp;http://www.ecdpm.org/Web_ECDPM/Web/Content/Content.nsf/7732def81dddfa7ac1256c240034fe65/b5b11d3bc24f45a7c1257241004efa1f?OpenDocument" target="_self">http://www.ecdpm.org/Web_ECDPM/Web/Content/Navigation.nsf/index2?readfor...</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Indications as to the progress in the Pacific-EU EPA negotiations are somewhat confused. On the one hand ‘a constructive atmosphere’ and a commitment to conclude by the end of 2007 and on the other an exchange of letters indicating that the progress is far from adequate. In a pre-Christmas letter to Trade Commissioner Mandelson, Pacific spokesperson Hans Jochim Kiel of Samoa expressed the belief that ‘there seems to have been little progress on the negotiations to date, implying ... the outlook for progress until the end of next year is somewhat bleak’. He called for a constructive response from the EC to Pacific concerns and not merely ‘a blanket reiteration of Commission ‘red lines’’. The minister rejected the exercise of ‘pressure due to the pressing deadline’, since this risked ending up with ‘a bad EPA’, which ‘would be disastrous’. Having critically reviewed progress, the letter focused on key areas, namely: </p>
<ul>

<li> the immediate granting of EBA-equivalent access (full duty-free/quota-free access) to the EU market;</li>

<li> clarity on the treatment of sugar;</li>

<li> the inclusion of a regional fisheries framework agreement;</li>

<li> modification of the rules of origin on the basis of a change in tariff sub-heading;</li>

<li> a well designed chapter on trade in services, including mode for access for skilled nationals;</li>

<li> investment provisions dealing with rights and responsibilities of investors, the home government and the host government, the provision of technical-assistance support and increased support for investment, including through a revision of EIB-managed facilities and an expanded role for the CDE and the CTA;</li>

<li> an EPA-adjustment facility with additional financial resources and appropriate swift procedures.</li>

</ul>
<p> The letter was accompanied by formal submissions in the various areas outlined. It concluded ‘we have demonstrated our commitment to these negotiations through the preparation of detailed, innovative and WTO-compatible proposals in a wide range of areas of central importance to both our sides. To date, by and large they have been met with what certainly appear to be rigid red lines, and inflexible positions that do not reflect any genuine willingness to think creatively and arrive at a mutually acceptable solution that addresses the unique needs and circumstances of the ‘P’ in the ACP. It is unclear what actual progress was made in January 2007 on the substantive issues set out in the December 2006 letter from Mr Kiel.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
